00:00:08.910 --> 00:00:15.679
Stranger Visions is a project by Heather Dewey-Hagborg
where she uses DNA to create portrait sculptures

00:00:15.679 --> 00:00:17.909
of people she has never met.

00:00:17.909 --> 00:00:23.970
To create them she collected DNA from cigarette
butts, hair, gum, and other sample and then

00:00:23.970 --> 00:00:30.210
used software to translate the DNA into computer
models and made 3D printed sculptures.

00:00:30.210 --> 00:00:33.630
Here she is with her own DNA 3D printed sculpture.&nbsp;

00:00:33.630 --> 00:00:38.380
Italian designer Umberto Dattola made this
giant furniture collection called Envi.

00:00:38.380 --> 00:00:44.810
He used old chairs, armchairs, dressers, and
beds and added extremely long legs to them

00:00:44.810 --> 00:00:46.490
so they overlooked everything.

00:00:46.490 --> 00:00:50.200
Turning antique furniture into surreal pieces
of art that seem to tell a story of their

00:00:50.200 --> 00:00:51.200
own.&nbsp;

00:00:51.200 --> 00:00:55.510
Etsy artist Ellen Jewett makes animal sculptures
that combine both realism and fantasy.

00:00:55.510 --> 00:01:00.500
She went to school for Biological Anthropology
and Fine Art and combined her passions into

00:01:00.500 --> 00:01:01.650
these works of art.

00:01:01.650 --> 00:01:03.670
&nbsp;Check out her Etsy page to see them all.

00:01:03.670 --> 00:01:06.409
Art teacher Michael Kohl paints custom shoes.

00:01:06.409 --> 00:01:10.320
After trying it out for fun he had a lot of
interest from others for his one of a kind

00:01:10.320 --> 00:01:11.320
creations.

00:01:11.320 --> 00:01:14.130
He now gives his customer the ability to pick
and choose exactly how the shoes look.

00:01:14.130 --> 00:01:18.969
All that you have to do is send your shoes
to him with a request of colors and theme

00:01:18.969 --> 00:01:22.109
and he will paint them for you and have them
back within a couple of weeks.

00:01:22.109 --> 00:01:27.021
Kohl was brought to me by one of his students
that thought he deserved to be in BiDiPi and

00:01:27.021 --> 00:01:28.259
I agreed.

00:01:28.259 --> 00:01:29.759
Check out his website for more!

00:01:29.759 --> 00:01:30.759
Draw It

00:01:30.759 --> 00:01:36.450
Kazuki Yamamoto and Kohei Matsuno of Osaka
are both artists that use lattes as their

00:01:36.450 --> 00:01:37.450
canvas.

00:01:37.450 --> 00:01:42.479
From 3D art like this cat, priceless pieces
of artwork like this replica of the scream,

00:01:42.479 --> 00:01:47.950
they are able to create momentary masterpieces
in 3-5 minutes that are consumed.

00:01:47.950 --> 00:01:52.159
Other examples are a monkey, peanuts characters
and Einstein.

00:01:52.159 --> 00:01:57.329
Nina Levy a mother of two and Brooklyn based
illustrator creates one of a kind art on napkins

00:01:57.329 --> 00:01:58.759
for her son's daily lunch.

00:01:58.759 --> 00:02:03.929
Over the last 6 years she's been using colored
markers to create pop culture-based artwork

00:02:03.929 --> 00:02:06.299
and to date has made over 2000 of them.

00:02:06.299 --> 00:02:09.720
She has a daily napkin blog where you can
check them out.

00:02:09.720 --> 00:02:14.360
